 Theory and Moral Responsibility -- tCHAPTER 17 A "Moral Core" Solution to the Prisoners' Dilemma -- tCHAPTER 18 Reinterpreting Risk -- tCHAPTER 19 Retrotopia: Critical Reason Turns Primitive -- tCHAPTER 20 International Society: What Is the Best that We Can Do? -- tAUTHOR NOTES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSchools of Thought brings together a cast of prominent scholars to assess, with unprecedented breadth and vigor, the intellectual revolution over the past quarter century in the social sciences. This collection of twenty essays stems from a 1997 conference that celebrated the twenty-fifth anniversary of the Institute for Advanced Study's School of Social Science. The authors, who represent a wide range of disciplines, are all associated with the School's emphasis on interpretive social science, which rejects models from the hard sciences and opts instead for a humanistic approach to social inquiry. Following a preface by Clifford Geertz, whose profound insights have helped shape the School from the outset, the essays are arranged in four sections. The first offers personal reflections on disciplinary changes; the second features essays advocating changes in focus or methodology; the third presents field overviews and institutional history; while the fourth addresses the link between political philosophy and world governance. Two recurring themes are the uses (and pitfalls) of interdisciplinary studies and the relation between scholarship and social change. This book will be rewarding for anyone interested in how changing trends in scholarship shape the understanding of our social worlds. The contributors include David Apter, Kaushik Basu, Judith Butler, Nicholas Dirks, Jean Elshtain, Peter Galison, Wolf Lepenies, Jane Mansbridge, Andrew Pickering, Mary Poovey, Istvan Rev, Renato Rosaldo, Michael Rustin, Joan W. Scott, William H. Sewell, Jr., Quentin Skinner, Charles Taylor, Anna Tsing, Michael Walzer, and Gavin Wright.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aSocial sciencesvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAlchemy.  aAnnales.  aBeyond Good and Evil.  aCirculation.  aConflations.  aDas Kapital.  aDefinitional Struggles.  aFuturism.  aGlobalization.  aHarvard Theological Review.  aOrientalism.  aPoetry.  aScale Making.  aSunset Magazine.  aThe German Ideology.  aThe Phenomenology.  aabsence.  aanalytically.  aannus mirabilis.  aanthropology.  aconatus.  acreative nonfiction.  adiscontinuity.  aexogenous.  aexplicit.  ahistoricizes interpretation.  ahumanity.  aidentity.  aideologies.  aimplication.  aincreasing returns.  aingredient.  ainterdisciplinarity.  amentalités.  amotherhood.  apenetration.  aphilosophy.  areality effect.  areductionist.  areferential illusion.  asituate.  atestimonio.  atransformation.1 aApter, David E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasu, Kaushik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirks, Nicholas B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElshtain, Jean Bethke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalison, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeertz, Clifford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeates, Debra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLepenies, Wolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMansbridge, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickering, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc